    <entry>
        <title type="html"><![CDATA[3 Things I Wish I Knew When I Started Learning to Code]]></title>
        <id>https://josearcani.com/blog/self-taught-lessons</id>
        <link href="https://josearcani.com/blog/self-taught-lessons"/>
        <updated>2025-03-05T00:00:00.000Z</updated>
        <summary type="html"><![CDATA[I came from an electronics engineering background and taught myself web]]></summary>
        <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p>I came from an electronics engineering background and taught myself web
development through books, FreeCodeCamp, and Udemy. Here are three things that
would have saved me time.</p>
<h2 class="anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id="1-build-things-before-you-feel-ready">1. Build things before you feel ready<a href="https://josearcani.com/blog/self-taught-lessons#1-build-things-before-you-feel-ready" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to 1. Build things before you feel ready" title="Direct link to 1. Build things before you feel ready">​</a></h2>
<p>Tutorials feel productive, but you only really learn when you get stuck on
your own project. My first MERN app was messy — and that's exactly why it
taught me more than any course.</p>
<h2 class="anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id="2-learn-debugging-not-just-coding">2. Learn debugging, not just coding<a href="https://josearcani.com/blog/self-taught-lessons#2-learn-debugging-not-just-coding" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to 2. Learn debugging, not just coding" title="Direct link to 2. Learn debugging, not just coding">​</a></h2>
<p>Knowing how to read stack traces, use breakpoints, and isolate problems is
more valuable than memorizing syntax. This skill compounds over time.</p>
<h2 class="anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id="3-pick-a-stack-and-go-deep">3. Pick a stack and go deep<a href="https://josearcani.com/blog/self-taught-lessons#3-pick-a-stack-and-go-deep" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to 3. Pick a stack and go deep" title="Direct link to 3. Pick a stack and go deep">​</a></h2>
<p>I spent months jumping between frameworks. Progress came when I committed to
the MERN/PERN stacks and built real projects with them. Breadth comes later.</p>]]></content>
